  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementations Across Three Major Go Projects\n\n### Kubernetes/Kubernetes\n\nKubernetes implements a sophisticated, plugin-based health check framework with three distinct endpoints:\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/healthz` - General health status\n- `/readyz` - Readiness probe\n- `/livez` - Liveness probe\n\n**Implementation Files:**\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go` - Core health check implementations\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go` - Endpoint registration functions\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go` - High-level API server integration\n\n**Key Registration Functions:**\n- `InstallHandler()` - Registers `/healthz` endpoint with pluggable health checks\n- `InstallReadyzHandler()` - Registers `/readyz` endpoint\n- `InstallLivezHandler()` - Registers `/livez` endpoint\n- `AddHealthChecks()`, `AddBootSequenceHealthChecks()`, `AddReadyzChecks()` - Methods in GenericAPIServer to add custom checks\n\n**Built-in Health Checks:**\n1. **PingHealthz** - Always returns healthy (baseline check)\n2. **LogHealthz** - Verifies logging can flush within 2 minutes, indicating the process isn't hung\n3. **InformerSyncHealthz** - Checks if Kubernetes informers (caches) have synchronized, critical for controllers and schedulers\n4. **ShutdownHealthz** - Fails during graceful shutdown to signal readiness systems to stop routing traffic\n\n**Features:**\n- Supports query parameters: `?verbose` for detailed check results, `?exclude=checkname` to skip specific checks\n- Thread-safe health check registry using sync.Mutex\n- Returns 200 OK if all checks pass, 500 if any check fails\n- Allows custom HealthChecker implementations for application-specific checks\n- Sophisticated graceful shutdown support via ShutdownHealthz\n\n### Grafana/Grafana\n\nGrafana implements a simpler, state-based health check system with atomic synchronization:\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/healthz` - Basic health status\n- `/livez` - Liveness probe\n- `/readyz` - Readiness probe\n- `/api/health` - Extended health with database status\n\n**Implementation Files:**\n- `pkg/server/health.go` - Core health endpoint handlers and HealthNotifier\n- `pkg/server/module_server.go` - Integration with module system\n- `pkg/api/http_server.go` - HTTP server setup\n\n**Key Registration Function:**\n- `RegisterHealthEndpoints()` - Registers both `/livez` and `/readyz` handlers with the HTTP router\n\n**Health Check Implementation:**\n1. **LivezHandler** - Always returns HTTP 200 with \"Grafana is Healthy.\" - simple liveness indicator that the process is running\n2. **ReadyzHandler** - Checks `HealthNotifier.IsReady()` state:\n   - Returns 200 OK with \"Grafana is Ready.\" when ready\n   - Returns 503 Service Unavailable when not ready\n3. **HealthNotifier** - Atomic boolean-based state manager:\n   - `SetReady()` and `SetNotReady()` for state transitions\n   - `IsReady()` for current status queries\n   - Thread-safe using atomic.Bool for concurrent access\n\n**Features:**\n- No complex dependency checks; readiness is controlled by operators via HealthNotifier\n- Operators can signal readiness state through dependency injection\n- Supports both GET and HEAD request methods\n- Simple state model (Ready/NotReady) without intermediate states\n- Database health available via separate `/api/health` endpoint\n\n### Prometheus/Prometheus\n\nPrometheus uses a different naming convention and implements a three-state ready status system:\n\n**Endpoints:**\n- `/-/healthy` - Liveness probe (always returns 200)\n- `/-/ready` - Readiness probe (state-dependent)\n\n**Implementation File:**\n- `web/web.go` - Single file containing both endpoint handlers and state management (lines 591-677)\n\n**Key Registration Functions:**\n- `New()` - Handler constructor that registers endpoints inline\n- `SetReady()` - Updates ready status and internal metrics\n- `testReady()` - Wrapper function that enforces readiness checks\n\n**ReadyStatus State Machine:**\nPrometheus uses a ReadyStatus enum with three states:\n1. **NotReady** - Service cannot accept requests, returns 503\n2. **Ready** - Normal operation, returns 200\n3. **Stopping** - Graceful shutdown in progress, returns 503 with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` header\n\n**Health Check Implementation:**\n1. **`/-/healthy`** - Always returns 200 with \"Prometheus is Healthy.\"\n   - No state checking, purely indicates process is alive\n2. **`/-/ready`** - Wrapped through `testReady()`:\n   - Returns 200 OK with \"Prometheus is Ready.\" when status is Ready\n   - Returns 503 Service Unavailable for NotReady or Stopping states\n   - Sets `X-Prometheus-Stopping` header to distinguish between stopping and not-yet-ready\n\n**Features:**\n- State management uses atomic operations for thread safety\n- Metrics integration: `metrics.readyStatus` gauge tracks state (1=Ready, 0=NotReady/Stopping)\n- Supports both GET and HEAD methods\n- Distinguishes graceful shutdown (Stopping state) from initialization (NotReady state)\n- No complex dependency checks; readiness is determined by internal initialization state\n\n## Comparison Summary\n\n**Complexity:**\n- Kubernetes: Most sophisticated with pluggable health checks and component-specific checks\n- Grafana: Simple state-based approach with operator integration\n- Prometheus: Lightweight state machine with three-state readiness\n\n**Dependency Checks:**\n- Kubernetes: Extensive (informer sync, logging, etcd, custom checks)\n- Grafana: Database checks available separately; readiness delegated to operators\n- Prometheus: No built-in dependency checks; state-based only\n\n**Naming Convention:**\n- Kubernetes: Standard `/healthz` and `/readyz` format\n- Grafana: Standard format plus `/api/health` for extended checks\n- Prometheus: Non-standard `/-/healthy` and `/-/ready` format\n\n**Thread Safety:**\n- Kubernetes: sync.Mutex for registry protection\n- Grafana: atomic.Bool for thread-safe state\n- Prometheus: atomic operations for state and metrics\n\n**Graceful Shutdown:**\n- Kubernetes: Dedicated ShutdownHealthz check that fails during shutdown\n- Grafana: SetNotReady() called during shutdown\n- Prometheus: Stopping state with distinct header to indicate graceful shutdown phase"
}

